summaries.title: Summary 305.1
summaries.summaryText: Ethan noted that successful project outcomes often came from teams with diverse backgrounds and perspectives. He believes empathy and active listening should be core engineering competencies. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Summary 305.2
summaries.summaryText: Ethan noted that successful project outcomes often came from teams with diverse backgrounds and perspectives. He believes empathy and active listening should be core engineering competencies. [Part 4/4]

timelinePoints.eventDescription: Became lead designer on the robotics team, guiding a diverse group of underclassmen through competition preparation. [Timeline 2]
Joined the Society of Hispanic Professional Engineers during her first semester to find community and mentorship. [Timeline 2]
Faced subtle exclusion in a group design project where her ideas were initially dismissed. [Timeline 4]

themes.title: Emotional Labor and Advocacy Burden in Underrepresented Students
themes.description: Aaliyah’s experience illustrates how women of color in engineering often balance advocacy roles with academic demands, leading to invisible emotional labor that institutions rarely acknowledge. [Extended 4]

themes.title: Team Diversity as an Engineering Strength
themes.description: Ethan believes interdisciplinary and culturally diverse teams drive better innovation outcomes, reflecting the growing importance of social awareness in engineering practice. [Extended 2]

themes.title: First-Generation Adaptation to STEM Rigor
themes.description: Luis’s story demonstrates resilience through peer and cultural support. [Extended 4]

quotes.quoteText: I love leading projects, but it’s exhausting always being the one to explain why diversity matters in engineering teams. [Context 4]
Sometimes I feel like everyone else just gets it — like I’m pretending to belong in these classes. [Context 4]
You can’t innovate if you’re burned out — STEM needs to start treating wellness as part of success. [Context 3]
At first I thought I wasn’t smart enough, but then I realized everyone’s struggling; we just don’t talk about it. [Context 1]
I love leading projects, but it’s exhausting always being the one to explain why diversity matters in engineering teams. [Context 3]
Sometimes I look around my class and I’m the only Latina — it makes me question whether I belong here. [Context 1]
You can’t innovate if you’re burned out — STEM needs to start treating wellness as part of success. [Context 3]

areasForImprovement.title: Integrate Wellness Programming into STEM Curriculum
areasForImprovement.description: Develop optional workshops or credit modules linking mental health and STEM performance. [Extended 2]

areasForImprovement.title: Normalize Academic Struggle Through Faculty Messaging
areasForImprovement.description: Faculty can help counter imposter syndrome by sharing personal learning experiences, highlighting that mastery develops over time and through mistakes. [Extended 2]

areasForImprovement.title: Increase Mentorship for Women in Computing
areasForImprovement.description: Expand mentorship and career guidance for women and first-gen students. [Extended 1]
